\begin_layout Subsection
Central v.s.
 commercial banks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Where does this money come from? In most countries, a 
\emph on
central bank
\emph default
 (e.g., the Federal Reserve, BoJ, BoE, ECB) is responsible for controlling
 the supply of fiat currency.
 The bank that you likely use is a 
\emph on
commercial
\emph default
 or local bank, which takes direction from the central bank, but has some
 degree of autonomy.
 Somewhat surprisingly, banks do not need to have 1-to-1 collateralization
 of all their assets and balances (
\shape italic
narrow banking
\shape default
).
 Instead, most world economies use the principle of 
\shape italic
fractional reserve banking
\shape default
 where money is created through loans that are issued to customers (the
 most familiar being a consumer real estate loan).
 Consider the following example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You deposit 100 dollars.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The bank puts 30 dollars in its reserves (30%).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
70 dollars are lent out to someone else
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are now 100 dollars + 70 dollars in circulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bank is not fully collateralizing its liabilities (100 dollars) with
 assets (30 dollars).
 In this system, if a 
\shape italic
bank run
\shape default
 were to happen, there would not be enough money for everyone to withdraw.
 What's more, the customer who took on a loan for 70 dollars can now go
 to another bank, which in turn can store 21 dollars (30%) in its reserves
 and borrow 49 dollars to another customer.
 The 
\shape italic
money multiplier
\shape default
 is the total amount of money that can be created for every dollar spent
 in this way.
 It is easy to prove that it's equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the reserve ratio
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This result stems from the underlying geometric series 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}(1-r)^{i}D_{0}=\frac{D_{0}}{r}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the initial deposit.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The total amount of money that can be created in this way for an initial
 deposit of 100 dollars is therefore 333.33...
 dollars.
 
